{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:13:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:13:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"639"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582703"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:52:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:52:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"639"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/639"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.69,0.22,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/639"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37105"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"492"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 87-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her daughter, who is her carer, with a three-month history of poor appetite and weight loss. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The patient lives with her daughter. She is able to care for herself but does have some difficulties dressing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. After assessment, a CT scan is organised, which shows a large para-oesophageal hernia. Your specialists opinion is that she would benefit from laparoscopic repair of her hiatus hernia, and that she is at risk of malnutrition if she does not undergo surgical repair. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe daughter is agreeable to the procedure, but the patient is apprehensive, and insists that provided she keeps to small meals her appetite is fine. On further questioning, she understands the risks of not having the surgery and is adamant that she does not want to have it. The daughter insists that her mother is not eating well and wants the hernia repaired.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apply to make the daughter a substitute decision maker and proceed with the surgery","Respect the patient\u0027s expressed views","Perform a Mini-Mental State Examination","Seek a Guardianship Board opinion","Inquire about Advance Care Directives"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents an ethical dilemma involving patient autonomy and capacity to make medical decisions. The most appropriate course of action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erespect the patient\u0027s expressed views\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient demonstrates capacity to make an informed decision about her medical care, even though it conflicts with medical advice and her daughter\u0027s wishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECapacity is the ability to make a specific decision at a particular time. In this case, the patient shows she can understand the information about the proposed treatment and its alternatives, retain this information, weigh the relevant factors, and communicate her decision. There is no indication that her mental state is impaired or that she lacks capacity to make this decision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplying to make the daughter a substitute decision maker\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and unethical when the patient has demonstrated capacity to make her own decisions. This would violate the principle of patient autonomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming a Mini-Mental State Examination\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this scenario. The patient has demonstrated understanding and reasoning ability specific to this medical decision, which is more relevant than a general cognitive assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeeking a Guardianship Board opinion\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overreach at this stage. Guardianship is typically sought when a person lacks capacity to make decisions, which is not evident here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInquiring about Advance Care Directives\u003C/strong\u003E is not directly relevant to this immediate decision. While it may be beneficial for future planning, it does not address the current situation where the patient is capable of expressing her own wishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the clinician may disagree with the patient\u0027s decision from a medical perspective, it is crucial to respect the patient\u0027s autonomy when she has demonstrated capacity. However, it would be appropriate to schedule a follow-up appointment to allow the patient time to further consider her decision and discuss it with her family without pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with full mental capacity, it is important to respect their views above the views of their family members when there is conflict.","Capacity to make medical decisions is specific to the decision at hand and the time it is being made."],"references":["Longo DL. Enduring and Emerging Challenges of Informed Consent. N Engl J Med 2015; 372:855-62. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1411250"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37105"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"639"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37105"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-29T20:05:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-29T20:06:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"639"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","posi